# Security headers. Copied verbatim into the build output, applied to every
# response.
#
# The CSP is the trust ladder, enforced by the browser rather than promised in a
# privacy policy. `connect-src` is an ALLOWLIST of every host this app may ever
# talk to. If a host is not on this line, the browser refuses the request — so a
# tampered script cannot exfiltrate a passphrase, a balance, or an address to
# anywhere else.
#
# Every entry below must be justifiable as a tier on the ladder (see CLAUDE.md).
# Adding a host here is a security decision, not a config tweak. Review it.
#
#   'self'                    — the app's own origin.
#   ballast-server…workers.dev — our sync server. Tier 0: it only ever sees
#                               opaque ciphertext + non-secret metadata, never the
#                               passphrase or the key. A compromise yields blobs.
#   blockstream.info          — tier 1. Public Bitcoin chain data. Learns which
#                               BTC addresses you watch. Nothing else.
#   cloudflare-eth.com        — tier 1. Public Ethereum JSON-RPC. Same deal.
#   api.coingecko.com         — tier 1. Public market prices. Learns which assets
#                               you hold, NOT how much.
#   api.alpaca.markets        — tier 2. Your own brokerage, reached directly with
#   paper-api.alpaca.markets    your own read-only API key. Alpaca already holds
#                               the account; nobody new learns anything. The key
#                               travels to this host and can travel nowhere else —
#                               that is precisely what this line enforces.
#
# There is no analytics host here, and there never will be. There is no font CDN
# here either — fonts are system-native, so `font-src 'self'` can stay absolute.
#
# `wasm-unsafe-eval` (script-src): permits compiling WebAssembly — and ONLY that;
# it does not permit JS eval(). Needed by the on-device receipt reader (ocr.ts),
# whose engine is WASM served from our own origin. The name is scarier than the
# grant: the wasm still has to come from a script-src-permitted origin, which
# remains 'self' alone.
/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' 'wasm-unsafe-eval'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data: blob:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' https://ballast-server.jdd994.workers.dev https://blockstream.info https://cloudflare-eth.com https://api.coingecko.com https://api.alpaca.markets https://paper-api.alpaca.markets; manifest-src 'self'; worker-src 'self'; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'; form-action 'none'; upgrade-insecure-requests
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Referrer-Policy: no-referrer
  # camera=(self): granted 2026-07-17, for one feature — the receipt scan
  # assist — under explicit terms: the camera activates only on the user's tap,
  # frames are processed on this device in memory and discarded, nothing is
  # stored until the shutter, nothing ever leaves (connect-src enforces that),
  # and the stream stops the moment the sheet closes. Declining the permission
  # leaves the photo-picker path fully working. Nothing else may use this
  # grant. Everything else stays locked.
  Permissions-Policy: camera=(self), microphone=(), geolocation=(), interest-cohort=(), payment=()
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
